            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Mark Leung\u2019s story begins with a loving contradiction: a fair-haired, blue-eyed boy adopted by a Chinese-American family in Cleveland, Ohio. His father, an engineer, and his mother, a seamstress, raised him in a home filled with the smell of his mother\u2019s cooking and the quiet hum of his father\u2019s drafting table. While he cherished his family, his appearance made him an outsider in both the local white and Chinese communities, instilling in him a quiet, observant nature and a deep appreciation for things that were well-made and fit together perfectly.\n\nSchool was a challenge, but he found his calling in shop class. Fascinated by systems and mechanics, he pursued an Associate's degree in Industrial Technology at a local community college. He started his career on the factory floor of an automotive parts supplier, his sharp mind and strong work ethic helping him climb from line operator to shift supervisor. The key turning point came at 28 when a former boss recruited him for a management position at a specialty food production plant in San Francisco\u2019s Dogpatch neighborhood. It was a terrifying and thrilling leap.\n\nIn San Francisco, Mark found a strange sense of home. He settled in the Inner Richmond, a neighborhood whose vibrant Chinese culture felt like a familiar echo of his upbringing. For fifteen years, he was with a partner, a librarian named David, and they built a quiet life together. The breakup five years ago was amicable but left Mark adrift, reinforcing his solitary tendencies.\n\nToday, Mark\u2019s life runs with the precision of the production lines he manages. He wakes at 5:30 AM, catching the N Judah Muni downtown before transferring to the T Third Street line. His day is a blur of logistics, quality control, and mentoring younger workers, a role he finds increasingly fulfilling. He takes pride in the tangible product his plant creates. Evenings are for walks in Golden Gate Park or cooking simple, hearty meals. His dream isn't to climb higher or get rich; it\u2019s to save enough to retire comfortably, maybe do some part-time consulting, and finally visit the provinces in China his parents came from, connecting the last piece of his own intricate, well-made life."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.  He remembers standing in the kitchen of his childhood home in Cleveland, maybe seven years old. His mother was showing him how to fold the edges of a wonton wrapper, her nimble fingers a blur. He tried to mimic her, but his were clumsy. When he finally made one that held its shape, she smiled and praised his \u201cengineer\u2019s hands,\u201d just like his father. He felt a quiet, perfect click of belonging, a sense of being well-made, even if his blue eyes didn\u2019t match theirs. It was his first lesson in craftsmanship.\n\n2.  The engine sputtered, then caught. He was nineteen, in the loud, oil-scented workshop of his community college. He\u2019d spent a week carefully disassembling, cleaning, and reassembling the small motor. As it hummed smoothly on the bench, a feeling of deep, uncomplicated rightness settled in his chest. For the first time, a system made perfect sense to him, and he had made it work. This quiet victory was more profound than any A+ on a test; it was the moment he knew his path forward wasn't academic, but mechanical.\n\n3.  His first Saturday in San Francisco, adrift and 28. He took the bus to the Inner Richmond, and the moment he stepped onto Clement Street, the anxiety eased. The smells of roast duck and herbal medicines, the specific cadence of Cantonese spoken by the grandmothers\u2014it was the background music of his youth, but here, no one stared at him. He was just another person on a busy street. It wasn't about fitting in; it was the relief of being able to observe a familiar world without being an anomaly in it.\n\n4.  A quiet Sunday afternoon about ten years ago. Fog was thick outside the window of their apartment. David was lost in a book, curled in their big armchair. Mark was at the kitchen table, meticulously re-seasoning the cast iron pan his mother had given him. The only sounds were the turning of a page and the soft\u64e6 of his cloth on the metal. There was no need to speak. The silent, parallel contentment felt like a perfectly calibrated machine, the most peaceful his life had ever been.\n\n5.  Just last year, a young hire named Maria was flustered by a jam in the labeling machine. Instead of fixing it himself, Mark stood beside her, asking quiet questions until she diagnosed the problem on her own. He saw the flash of pride and understanding in her eyes\u2014the same feeling he\u2019d had with that first engine. In that moment, his job wasn\u2019t about output quotas. It was about passing on a way of seeing. It was a new kind of fulfillment, less mechanical and more human."
